The unfortunate rivality which existed between the glass and the oil painters appears to have had no small share in this; anxious to excel and emulative of accomplishing what had previously been, apparently, unattempted, the glass painters wandered from the legitimate conditions of their art in striving to rival the delicacy and gradations os the air tints, which they so much admired in the productions of their brother artists, totally forgetting that the means by which their works were rendered visible, a transmitted light, demanded a treatment so widely different. The experience of the past was neglected‚ and the art gradually sank, only to be revived by a return to the practice which elevated it.
